<DOC><DOCNO> AP890906-0156 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1603EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Gambino-Drugs     09-06 0252</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Gambino-Drugs,0258</SECOND><HEAD>Alleged Heroin Kingpin Convicted</HEAD><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Reputed drug kingpin Francesco Gambino andfour associates have been convicted for their roles in aSicilian-based network that imported and sold millions of dollarsworth of heroin between 1984 and 1988.   Gambino, 48, of New York City, was found guilty Tuesday by afederal jury on charges of conspiring to smuggle and distributeheroin. Gambino and his co-defendants face up to 30 years in prison.No sentencing date was set.   Also convicted were Ignazio Antonino Mannino, on charges ofconspiring to import and distribute heroin; Emanuele SalvatoreMannino and Grace Pulitano Mannino, both on the two conspiracycharges and a charge of money laundering; and Enzo Varisco, on acharge of conspiring to distribute more than five kilograms ofcocaine.   One defendant, Carlo Fodera, was found innocent. Varisco wasfound innocent of conspiring to distribute heroin.   District Judge Louis C. Bechtle revoked Gambino's bail andordered him taken into custody. Gambino had been confined to hishouse, wearing a security bracelet and having his telephone callsmonitored.   His attorney, David Breitbart, said the conviction would beappealed. He contended during the trial his client had been targetedbecause authorities mistakenly believed he was related to the lateNew York mob boss Carlo Gambino.   Authorities have said 68 people were charged in the United Statesand 133 in Italy after a three-year FBI undercover operation inwhich agents traveled to Italy and posed as interested buyers whodiscussed making major drug buys.</TEXT></DOC>